:: kidKgate3
Finally, flames can become a blaze. 

Starting from the middle of the keyboard, find two keys that have one key between them, like a flame. Put one finger from your hand on the left key, and your adult should put one finger from their hand, on the right key.
<<linkreplace "Tap to continue." t8n>>
Play the two keys like a flame, then, move both of your hands one key outwards, so there’s now a gap of three notes in between. Play them back and forth, as a trill. Then, move outwards again. How big can you make the blaze? 

Play with the sparks and the flames, then, when the fire feels very big, both of you should make a blaze together. When you feel you can make all three sound different from each other, tap ‘Next’.

[[Next|kidKgate4]]
<</linkreplace>>
:: kidKgate4
Finally, imagine you’re making a film about a fire, from the first spark, to the ashes it leaves behind. The things that you’re pointing your imaginary camera at are the things your audience hears in the music. The sparks, the flames, and the blaze.
<<linkreplace "Tap to continue." t8n>>
Talk out loud about the story of the fire, so that you can create this piece together. Describe what you’re pointing the camera at, and make it happen in the music. Try directing each other.

Bring the piece to a close, by finding a way to show the heat and light fading. What do ashes sound like?
